Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.77,0:00:22.86,Default,,0,0,0,,The following talk is about a very relevant piece of technological legacy of um, our human race
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.86,0:00:27.54,Default,,0,0,0,,The first piece of computer that landed on uh, our moon
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.54,0:00:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And actually it became a metric, people started to compare other architectures
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.70,0:00:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,other computers in volumes of multiples of processing speed of this computer
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.62,0:00:44.54,Default,,0,0,0,,It's rocket science, but it's even harder, it's computer rocket science
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.54,0:00:50.86,Default,,0,0,0,,So I'm very happy to have Christian Hessmann or Hesse on stage, who is actually a rocket scientist
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.86,0:00:58.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And for the...for the computer part we have Michael Steil, who is the founder or the XBox Linux project
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.86,0:01:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And has gathered with this project and many others, lots and lots of experience around architectures of computers
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.18,0:01:08.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So please give a warm round of applause for the Ultimate Apollo Guidance Talk!
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.10,0:01:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome!
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.66,0:01:22.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Is this on? Anyone can hear me?  --Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.80,0:01:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome to the Ultimate Apollo Guidance Computer Talk
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.50,0:01:29.38,Default,,0,0,0,,aka a comprehensive introduction into computer architecture...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.38,0:01:31.12,Default,,0,0,0,,aka a comprehensive introduction into computer architecture...and operating systems...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.12,0:01:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,aka a comprehensive introduction into computer architecture...and operating systems...and space flight.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.28,0:01:36.44,Default,,0,0,0,,My name is Michael Steil.  --And I'm Christian Hessmann.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.90,0:01:40.62,Default,,0,0,0,,This talk is number six in a series by various people
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.90,0:01:45.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The idea is to explain as much as possible about a classical computer system in 60 minutes
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.62,0:01:50.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The Apollo Guidance Computer, AGC, is a digital computer that was designed from scratch
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.06,0:01:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,specifically for use onboard the Apollo spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.02,0:01:56.98,Default,,0,0,0,,To support the Apollo moon landings between 1969 and 1972
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.42,0:02:04.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Developed at MIT between 1961 and 1966, a total 42 AGCs were built, at a cost of about 200,000 dollars each
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.94,0:02:08.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The base clock is about 1 megahertz, all data are 15 bits
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.38,0:02:12.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And there are 2 kilowords of RAM and 36 kiloword ROM...words of ROM
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.82,0:02:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It's about the size of a large suitcase, weighs 32 kilograms, and consumes about 55 watts.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.90,0:02:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,It's user interface is a numeric display and keyboard.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.50,0:02:23.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Some historical context.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.26,0:02:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,In the mid-1960s, you couldn't just err...take an off-the-shelf computer and put it into the spacecraft.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.66,0:02:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,The first mini computerwass the size of a small fridge
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.78,0:02:36.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Too heavy, too power hungry and too slow for real time scientific calculations
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.14,0:02:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Even though the industry had come a long way since the previous decade
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.86,0:02:43.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Already 10 years later though, microcomputers with highly intergrated circuits
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.86,0:02:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,started outclassing the AGC hardware in many regards
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.10,0:02:49.82,Default,,0,0,0,,There's many reasons that make AGC specially interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.82,0:02:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,The architecture is very 60s and feels very alien to us today
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.98,0:02:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The hardware is very innovated for its time
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.48,0:03:01.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It has some very interesting and unusual peripherals
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.86,0:03:04.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Its operating system was revolutionary for its time
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.44,0:03:08.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And the mission software has all the bits too, with the right hardware attached fly you to the moon
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.80,0:03:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In the Apollo program, the Apollo Guidance Computer was used in two unmanned test missions
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.12,0:03:18.54,Default,,0,0,0,,where with the remote control from the ground, and three manned test missions
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.54,0:03:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And the seven manned landing missions
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.14,0:03:24.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Astronauts hated the idea of giving any control to a computer
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.30,0:03:26.22,Default,,0,0,0,,They wanted to be in charge
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.22,0:03:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,While it's a fallback, most of the mission could also be flown manually
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.00,0:03:30.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The mission planners got their way
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.14,0:03:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,To understand the purpose and responsibilities of the Apollo Guidance Computer
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.14,0:03:35.94,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to first look at the Apollo mission
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.94,0:03:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The core strategy of the Apollo program was, instead of landing a complete spacecraft on the moon
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.66,0:03:43.60,Default,,0,0,0,,for which an extremely large rocket would have been required
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.60,0:03:48.62,Default,,0,0,0,,To land a much smaller lander while the larger part with the fuel for the way back stays in the moon orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.98,0:03:53.78,Default,,0,0,0,,So the Apollo spacecraft can be separated into the lunar module, the command module and the service module
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.78,0:03:59.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The Saturn-V rocket launches it and three astronauts from K...Kennedy into earth orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.36,0:04:05.62,Default,,0,0,0,,By accelerating at the right time, the trans-lunar injection moved the spacecraft into a so-called free return orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.62,0:04:08.86,Default,,0,0,0,,By just coasting, and we'll travel on the moon and back to earth
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.86,0:04:14.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Right at the beginning of this 3-day journey, the command, service module extracts the lunar module and docks with it
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.18,0:04:19.10,Default,,0,0,0,,By braking on the far side of the moon, the spacecraft enters a lunar orbit
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.10,0:04:23.02,Default,,0,0,0,,After two of the astronauts have climbed into the lunar module
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.02,0:04:27.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And after undocking, the lunar module brakes. This is called "powered descent"
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.20,0:04:32.38,Default,,0,0,0,,...and lands.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.24,0:04:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,After taking off again, the lunar module on the cruise with the command service module
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.36,0:04:45.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And the two astronauts climbed to the command module, and the lunar module is jettisoned
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.78,0:04:50.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The remaining command and service module accelerates at the far side of moon for trajectory towards earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.30,0:04:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,For entry only the command module remains.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.02,0:04:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,By the way, this excellent visualizations are form Jered Owen's "How the Apollo Works" videos
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.32,0:04:59.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Which we can highly recommend
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.18,0:05:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The command service module and the lunar module each contained one AGC
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.02,0:05:08.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It was the same hardware, but attached to partially different IO devices
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.42,0:05:10.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and with the software adapted for the specific spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.98,0:05:14.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The astronauts interact with them through the display and keyboard units
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.98,0:05:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Which are mounted alongside these hundreds of switches
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.30,0:05:23.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The computer's responsibilities during the mission are to track the position and speed
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.92,0:05:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,the so called state vector for both spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.25,0:05:30.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Stabilize spacecraft's attitude, calculate and control engine burns
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.20,0:05:34.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And monitor or control the Saturn V during launch
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.57,0:05:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to understand how the Apollo computer does all this, we'll look at its architecture
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.95,0:05:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,the hardware implementation, some of its interesting peripherals
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.34,0:05:50.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The system software, as well as the mission software
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.22,0:05:56.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The architecture of the AGC can be described as VonNeumann accumulator machine
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.12,0:05:58.12,Default,,0,0,0,,with 15-bit one's complement, big-endian arithmetic,
